25

00:01:31,990  -->  00:01:35,890
It will have a method to create a tokenizer from text.

26

00:01:35,890  -->  00:01:38,910
It will have the encode method that will take

27

00:01:38,910  -->  00:01:42,830
a string and convert it into a list of token IDs.

28

00:01:42,830  -->  00:01:46,570
It will also have the decode method that does the opposite,

29

00:01:46,570  -->  00:01:51,850
it receives a list of token IDs and converts them into a text.

30

00:01:51,850  -->  00:01:56,850
The final method will return the vocabulary size or our tokenizer.

31

00:01:56,850  -->  00:02:00,050
Let's start implementing these one by one.

32

00:02:00,220  -->  00:02:03,740
The train from text method will receive the text

33

00:02:03,740  -->  00:02:06,600
that we will use to get the list of unique characters.

34

00:02:06,600  -->  00:02:11,435
It will use the set method to get all the distinct characters in the text.

35

00:02:11,435  -->  00:02:13,720
It will then convert them into a list,

36

00:02:13,720  -->  00:02:17,680
sort them and part to the chart tokenizer constructor.

37

00:02:17,680  -->  00:02:19,520
Now, for the constructor,

38

00:02:19,520  -->  00:02:25,460
our tokenizer will need to convert from characters to token IDs and vice versa.

39

00:02:25,460  -->  00:02:28,300
For this, we'll have two different maps.

40

00:02:28,300  -->  00:02:30,080
To construct these maps,

41

00:02:30,080  -->  00:02:33,105
we will iterate over the list of characters.

42

00:02:33,105  -->  00:02:35,770
For every character, we will get the character

43

00:02:35,770  -->  00:02:39,630
itself and its position in this vocabulary.

44

00:02:39,630  -->  00:02:44,250
Having these pairs of the position that we will make a token ID and the character,

45

00:02:44,250  -->  00:02:46,250
